title: For Sale/Trade:  TIPS FOR ARMSLIST LISTINGS
location: RALEIGH, DURHAM, CHAPEL AREA, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
This message is posted due to recent activity on this site.  The following information is based on personal experience and discussions with other reasonable readers of this site.

1. If you list on this site be honest about the condition of the item you wish to sell.  it saves everyone wasted time or inquiries.
2. If you list it, respond to inquiries.  Only take a few moments to send a reply to someone who responds to your listing.
3. If you sell your listing, deactivate it immediately.  This saves anyone else from sending a request to buy.  Also have some intregrety and complete the transaction as quickly as possible.  If a seller is unresponsive, flag their listing as unresponsive.
4. Create your listing with everything you want to sell shown in your listing.   Required paperwork  is the best for both seller and buyer.  If your make contact with a buyer share name and phone number so contact for meeting time and location is easy.  Buying some things on this site are like trying to crack a top secret file.
5. Always try to meet in at a business or public place.   Avoid night time meetings or going to someone's house.   better safe than sorry.
6. Do some research on the listed item before you make an offer.  If an item is used and not of special value check a gun site like Bud's Guns to determine the value of the item if it were new.  Way to many listed items are overvalued on this and other sites.   It is not resonable to pay more for a used firearm than a new one unless you are willing to pay the asking price.  There are added costs buying online or from a dealer so this site has merit if the price is right.
7. My personal favorite is the "make me an offer" listings.  Sounds like someone is lonely and wants emails.  If you post a listing let us buyers know what you would like for your listing and save our time responding with an insufficent offering.
8. Take time creating your listing.  Properly catorgize and list the value.  If you list "free" in the heading how do you charge for what you want to sell.  Proper listings agains saves us all and will help sell your product faster.
9.  Use the "Flags" to tag any listings that you have problems with. 
I have made posts at the Forum but many of the viewers of this site do not use the Forum section.  Thus the post here. 

I welcome response's to this post.   Maybe we can improve some of the communication and have an improved environment to sell, trade or buy our firearms.

title: For Sale:  1891 Argentine Mauser - 95%+ w/Solingen Brass Grip Bayonet
postcontent:
For sale today is a Mauser Model of 1891 made by Loewe of Berlin for Argentina. Many consider the Model of 1891 to be Mauser's greatest work, and the most beautiful of all the his rifles.

Craftsmanship and attention to detail was at a peak when this rifle was made and is very evident when inspecting it. Fit between wood and metal is simply excellent, and the machining of all the metal parts is second to none. The bolt is highly polished and actually appears to be chrome plated, but is not.

I'd rate the overall condition of the rifle at a conservative 95%. There are no traces of rust or corrosion and the wood is superb with only the slightest of handling and storage marks. The bore is excellent as well. 

Crest on this rifle has been removed like most of them because Argentina required it before releasing them. However work was done well and there is no ugly scar as a result. Then someone at some point touched up the bluing where the crest was so you have to look close to be able to tell there was a crest there to begin with. I've owned the rifle for 30 years and didn't do this work so it was completed a long time ago.

Every part that has a number matches including the receiver, barrel, bolt, stock, magazine, and even the cleaning rod. Additionally I cannot find any importer marks on the rifle anywhere so it may have came over before an importers mark was required. 

This rifle shoots the 7.65 x 53mm Argentine Mauser cartridge. Ammo is readily available from PPU, Graf, S&B, plus a few others, and it's relatively inexpensive. You can find it at Sportsman Guide, Aim Surplus, Graf &Sons, and Cabela's to name a few. 

Rifle comes with a correct leather sling and a model of 1891 Solingen bayonet with brass grips. The brass grip bayonet was only made between 1892 and mid-1893. After which the grip material was switched to aluminum in order to lighten the bayonet and reduce it's cost. There were about 40,000 bayonets produced with the brass grips as compared to about 190,000 with the aluminum. This bayonet is in excellent condition and ones in similar condition sell on eBay for as much as $200 by themselves.

Asking price is $600 includes the bayonet. I also have two boxes of PPU recent production, brass case, non-corrosive ammo that will go with this rifle.

The rifle is considered to be an antique so it's not subject to same rules as modern firearms. Buyer must simply be at least 18 years old. Transaction is FTF with pickup in Brandon.
